and Stevens, JJ.).

61 Trop v. Dulles, 356 U.S. 86, 101 (1958).

62 See Furman v. Georgia, supra note 34, at 380-384, and at 417-
420  (Burger,  CJ., and Powell, J., respectively, dissenting).
See  also,  Gregg v. Georgia, supra note 60, at  176-180;  and
Callins  v  Collins,  114 S.Ct. 1127 (1994)(judgement  denying
cert.)(Scalia, J., concurring).  Those who take  the  contrary
view  say that these provisions do no more than recognise  the
existence of the death penalty at the time of the adoption  of
the  Constitution,  but do not exempt it from  the  cruel  and
unusual  punishment  clause.   Furman  v  Georgia  at  283-284
(Brennan,  J., concurring); People v. Anderson, 493 P.2d  880,
886 (Cal. 1972)(Wright, CJ.).

