139 Id. For a discussion of the application of the principle of
proportionality  in  German Constitutional jurisprudence,  see
Currie, The Constitution of the Federal Republic of Germany 18-
20,  307-310  (Univ.  of Chicago Press)(1994).   Prof.  Currie
outlines  the  genesis of proportionality,  intimated  in  the
Magna  Carta and generally described by Blackstone, and  notes
that  it  was  further developed by Carl  Gottleib  Svarez,  a
celebrated  thinker  of  the  German  Enlightenment.   "Svarez
insisted  on proportionality both between ends and  means  and
between costs and benefits; both aspects of the principle  are
reflected  in the jurisprudence of the Constitutional  Court."
Currie at 307.

