<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>After Ross Perot was excluded from the presidential debates, the Reform Party filed 
suit September 23, 1996 against the Federal Elections Commission and the Commission 
on Presidential Debates demanding that Perot be allowed to participate. According to the 
suit, the exclusion of Perot and his running mate will result in "incalculable damage to 
their campaign." Perot argues, "Declaring the election essentially over for all 
candidates but two before a single debate takes place will only deepen the nation's 
cynicism about government." The suit also claims that the Commission on Presidential 
Debates failed to use an objective standard in deciding Perot could not participate. </P>

<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<PRE>  


IN UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT
FOR THE DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA

ROSS PEROT
7616 LBJ Freeway
Suite 727
Dallas, Texas 75251

PAT CHOATE
7616 LBJ Freeway
Suite 727
Dallas, Texas 75251

and

PEROT '96, INC.
7616 LBJ Freeway
Suite 727
Dallas, Texas 75251

Plaintiffs,

vs.

FEDERAL ELECTION COMMISSION
United States Attorney
999 E Street, N.W.
Washington, D.C. 20463

and the

COMMISSION ON PRESIDENTIAL DEBATES
c/o Registered Agent Janet Brown
601 13th Street, N.W.
Washington, D.C. 20005,

Defendants.

Cause No.


VERIFIED COMPLAINT FOR DECLATORY JUDGMENT AND INJUNCTIVE 
RELIEF 

NOW COME Plaintiffs Ross Perot, Pat Choate and Perot '96, Inc., by and through 
counsel, and complain against Defendants as follows: 


INTRODUCTION

1. Plaintiffs bring this action against Defendants to enjoin the Commission on 
Presidential Debates' ("CPD") violation of Federal Election Commission ("FEC") 
regulations, the Federal Election Campaign Act, and the Constitutional guarantees of free 
speech, free association, equal protection and due process. Plaintiffs also bring this action 
to compel the CPD to apply fairly, objectively and lawfully its Candidate Selection 
Criteria for participation in the 1996 general election debates. The failure of CPD to 
comply with FEC regulations and to enforce its own criteria is a neutral and non-partisan 
way have resulted in the exclusion of Plaintiffs Ross Perot and Pat Choate from the 1996 
presidential debates, thereby causing incalculable damage to their campaign. Determining 
the participants in the debates is a critical public function that will shape the American 
people's ability to make meaningful and informed balloting decisions for President and 
Vice President. In 1988 and 1992, exit polls showed that more voters based their 
balloting decision on the debates than on any other single factor. In 1992, for the first 
time the television audience increased for each consecutive debate, culminating in 91 
million viewers for the third and final presidential debate. In the CPD's own words: 
"These events have become central education forums which Americans expect, watch, 
and value." 

2. Declaring the election essentially over for all candidates but two before a single debate 
takes place will only deepen the nation's cynicism about government. The FEC has 
unlawfully delegated control over debate selection criteria to the five Democratic and five 
Republican members of the CPD, who, in turn, have forsworn their obligation to apply 
only objective candidate selection criteria and instead automatically certified the 
Democratic and Republican nominees and then forced all other to run a gauntlet of 
subjective and arbitrary criteria. Plaintiffs ask this Court to vindicate their most essential 
political rights and ensure that the American people have access to a meaningful political 
debate and a meaningful electoral choice. The Democratic and Republican parties should 
not be permitted to consolidate their monopoly on the political process by closing off the 
presidential debates to Plaintiffs Ross Perot and Pat Choate. 


THE PARTIES

3. Plaintiff Ross Perot ("Perot") is a natural born citizen of the United States, is qualified 
under the United States Constitution to hold the offing of President of the United States 
of America, and is the candidate of the Reform Party for that office. The Reform Party is 
a political association of affiliated voters who have established Reform Parties in the 50 
states. Perot's campaign has received approximately $29 million in pre-election funding 
from the Presidential Election Campaign Fund, based upon Perot's polling approximately 
19% of the votes cast in the 1992 presidential election. Perot is on the ballot as a 
candidate for President in the 50 states and the District of Columbia for the general 
election to be held November 5, 1996. 

4. Plaintiff Pat Choate ("Choate") is a natural born citizen of the United States, is 
qualified under the United States Constitution to hold the office of Vice President of the 
United States of America, and is the running mate of Perot. 

5. Plaintiff Perot' 96, Inc., ("Perot '96") is a duly incorporated campaign committee with 
its principal office in Dallas, Texas. It exists in accordance with Federal Election 
Commission rules and regulations for the purpose of serving as the authorized general 
election campaign committee of Perot 

6. Defendant Commission on Presidential Debates ("CPD") is a non-profit corporation 
organized under the laws of the District of Columbia It is recognized as exempt from 
taxation under Sec. 501(c)(3) of the Internal Revenue Code. From its inception, the CPD 
has been co-chaired by Frank J. Fahrenkopf, Jr., and Paul G. Kirk, Jr., Chairmen of the 
Republican and Democratic National Committee, respectively, at the time of CPD's 
organization. Membership on the CPD is and has always been restricted to, and divided 
equally among, representatives of the Democratic and Republican parties. All 
communications of the CPD carefully note Messrs. Fahrenkopf's and Kirk's status as 
former Republican and Democratic party chairmen. At all times relevant herein, 
Defendant CPD, through the conduct of its agents, employees, and/or directors, has acted 
under the color of authority of state law, to the unlawful detriment of Plaintiffs as 
hereinafter alleged. 

7. Defendant Federal Election Commission ("FEC") is an administrative agency of the 
United States Government created pursuant to the Federal Election Commission Act (the 
"Act"), 2 U.S.C. Sec. 437c. 


JURISDICTION, VENUE AND STANDING

8. Plaintiffs have jurisdiction and venue in this Court pursuant to 28 U.S.C. Sec. 1331, 2 
U.S.C.Sec. 437g(a)(8)(A), 28 U.S.C. Sec. 2201, and 42 U.S.C. Sec. 1983. Venue is 
proper in this Court pursuant to 28 U.S.C. Sec. 1391. There is now existing between the 
parties hereto an actual, justiciable controversy in respect to which Plaintiffs are entitled 
to have a declaration of rights and further relief, including permanent injunctive relief, 
because of the facts, conditions, and circumstances hereinafter set forth 

9. Plaintiffs have standing as aggrieved parties injured by the violation of the Act as more 
fully set forth herein. 

10. In 1985, the respective chairmen of the Democratic and Republican National 
Committees executed an agreement stating that the major parties would work together to 
sponsor presidential debates, and replace the debates sponsored by the League of Women 
Voters with nationally televised joint appearances conducted between the presidential and 
vice presidential nominees of the "two major political parties." 

11. Fifteen months later, the major parties issued a joint press release, as well as parallel 
separate press releases, announcing the incorporation of the CPD. The releases declared 
that the CPD was a "bi-partisan" organization and that it was formed to implement joint 
sponsorship of general election debates by the national Republican and Democratic 
Committees "between their respective nominees." 

12. In July 1987, the CPD formed an advisory committee to formulate criteria for 
selecting candidates other than those  of the Democratic and Republican parties. The 
committee recommended that the CPD invite only candidates who had a "realistic 
chance" of winning the general election. 

13. By July 1988, a year later, the CPD had not formulated any criteria to assess the 
"realistic chance" standard recommended by the advisory committee.  Rather, the CPD 
simply invited the Democratic and Republican candidates to debate without requiring that 
they apply, while third-party candidates were offered no application procedure 
whatsoever, 

14. In the Fall of 1988, after a prolonged dispute over debate sponsorship between the 
League of Women Voters and the CPD,a compromise was reached under which they 
agreed to alternate sponsorship The League withdrew, however, when the Bush and 
Dukakis campaigns presented the League with a script for every detail of the staging of 
the debates,ranging from selection of questioners to the color of the timer lights on the 
podiums. The League explained its withdrawal by stating that to hold itself out as an 
independent sponsor of such a production would make it "an accessory to the 
hoodwinking of the American public." 

15. After the League' withdrawal, the CPD became the sole sponsor of the 1988 debates. 
It followed the exact specifications of the Bush and Dukakis campaigns, which the 
League of Women Voters had refused to do.  The CPD functions as a partisan, albeit bi-
partisan, political committee, a committee affiliated with Democratic and Republican 
national committees and the campaign committees of their party nominees for president.  
The CPD acts as a production company for direct and in-kind contributions to the major 
parties.  These contributions are subsidized by the United States Treasury through tax 
deductible contributions to the CPD by large business corporation, foundations and other 
parties who either are barred from contributing at all to federal candidates, or who are 
subject to contribution ceilings.  These contributions made to the CPD, and by the CPD 
to the Republican Democratic candidates, violate prohibitions against corporate 
contributions generally and against contributions to major party candidates in the general 
election who have accepted payments from the Presidential Election Campaign Fund. 

16.  In 1992, Ross Perot was invited to participate in the presidential debates by the Bush 
and Clinton campaigns pursuant to an agreement between those campaigns which offered 
Perot, and the CPD, the opportunity to participate on a "take it or leave it basis."  On 
October 5, 1992, the Clinton and Bush campaigns submitted the agreement to the CPD, 
inviting it to sponsor the debates subject to the terms of the debate agreement, including 
the understanding that Perot would be invited to participate in the debates. The CPD then 
asked its Advisory Committee to evaluate Perot's participation under the CPD's criteria 
for third-party and independent candidates. By letter of the CPD to the Clinton and Bush 
campaign dated October 6, 1992, a copy of which is attached hereto as Exhibit A, the 
CPD accepted the invitation to sponsor the debate subject to various conditions and 
understandings, one of which was as follows: 


"The Commission has determined, pursuant to the recommendation of its non-partisan 
advisory committee on candidate selection, that H. Ross Perot and Adm. James Stockdale 
should be invited to participate the October 11 and 13, 1992 debates, respectively. The 
Commission will make its candidate participation determination regarding the October 15 
and 19 debates after the initial debates. The Commission understands that, if it 
subsequently determines not to invite Mr. Perot to additional debates under its 
sponsorship, you each reserve the right to seek an alternative sponsor for these debates." 


17. The Bush and Clinton campaigns responded to the CPD that if it did not extend the 
invitation to Perot for every debate, under the terms of the Bush/Clinton debate 
agreement they would find another debate sponsor. Ross Perot accepted the invitation to 
the debates pursuant to the Bush/Clinton debate agreement on October 6, 1992. Within 24 
hours the CPD capitulated advising the Bush and Clinton campaigns by letter of October 
7, 1992, a copy of which is attached hereto Exhibit B, as follows: 


"The Commission has determined that H. Ross Perot should be invited to participate in 
the October 11, 15 and 19 presidential debates and that Admiral James Stockdale should 
be invited to participate in the October 13 vice presidential debate." 


18. As the result of concerns raised about organizations staging presidential debates in 
1988 and 1992, the FEC adopted new regulations ("Debates Regulations"), effective 
March 13, 1996, which require every organization staging a presidential debate to comply 
with simple, straightforward candidate-selection guidelines, namely: 


"For all debates, staging organization(s) must use pre-established objective criteria to 
determine which candidates may participate in a debate.  For general election debates, 
staging organization(s) shall not use nomination by a particular political party as the sole 
objective criterion to determine whether to include a candidate in a debate." 


11 C.F.R. Sec. 110.13(c).

19.  Notwithstanding the mandate of this particular regulation, the CPD has insisted in 
applying its subjective Candidate Selection Criteria For 1996, adopted by the CPD on 
September 19, 1995, a copy of which is attached hereto as Exhibit C. These are virtually 
the same as the criteria used in 1992, as the CPD has publicly noted. 

20.  In its introductory statement to the criteria, the CPD states that the "goal" of the 
debates is: 


"[T]o afford the members of the voting public an opportunity to sharpen their views of 
those candidates from among whom the next President or Vice President will be selected.  
In light of the huge number of declared candidates in any given  presidential election, the 
Commission has determined that its voter education goal is best achieved by limiting 
debate participation to the next President and his or her principal rival(s)." 


21.  Pursuant to this criteria, the CPD automatically extends an invitation to the 
respective nominees of the two major parties.  Specifically, the CPD's selection criteria 
states: 


"A Democratic or Republican nominee has been elected to the Presidency for more than a 
century.  Such historical prominence and sustained voter interest warrants the extension 
of an invitation to the respective nominees of the two major parties to participate in the 
Commission's 1996 debates." 


22. The FEC Debates Regulation make no distinction between major and nonmajor 
parties as to application of the criteria to be applied in selecting candidates to debate. The 
Same "objective criteria" is to be applied to all. However, the criteria applied by the CPD 
contain a separate set of guidelines that are subjective, and are applied only in 
determining which "nonmajor" party candidates will be invited to participate in the 
debates.  The CPD states that it has developed such "nonpartisan criteria" for the purpose 
of "further[ing] the educational purposes of the debates," and identifying "nonmajor party 
candidates, if any,... who properly are considered to be among the principal rivals for the 
Presidency."  If that is so, the educational purpose is best fulfilled by having Perot, who is 
clearly deemed by the public as "among the principal rivals for the Presidency," in the 
debates. 

23.  The thrust of the subjective criteria is to invite only those third-party candidates who, 
in the opinion of the CPD, are considered to be among the principal rivals for the 
presidency.  However, the CPD acknowledges in the introduction to its selection criteria 
for nonmajor party candidates that such criteria "contemplate no quantitative threshold" 
for debate inclusion: 


"Rather, the Commission will employ a multifaceted analysis of potential electoral 
success, including a review of (1) evidence of national organization, (2) signs of national 
newsworthiness and competitiveness, and (3) indicators of national enthusiasm or 
concern, to determine whether a candidate has a sufficient chance of election to warrant 
inclusion in one or more if its debates." 


24.  Perot satisfies all objective CPD criteria for inclusion in the debates, and also all 
(impermissible) subjective criteria outlined above.  Perot '96 is a national organization. 
Ross Perot is deemed newsworthy and competitive as a "principal rival for the 
Presidency," and his campaign evidences national enthusiasm and concern, perhaps best 
demonstrated by the public outcry at the CPD's arbitrary decision and widely publicized 
public opinion polls showing a vast majority of voters believe that the decision was 
wrong and unfair. 

25.  In violation of FEC regulations, the CPD extended invitations to President Clinton 
and Senator Dole to participate in its debates solely on the basis of their nomination by 
the Democratic and Republican parties.  No subjective criteria of "realistic chance of 
winning the election" was applied to either Senator Dole or President Clinton, and no 
pundits were polled on the issue. 

26.  Based on information and belief, representatives of the CPD have had ongoing 
substantive communications with representatives of the Clinton campaign, the Dole 
campaign, the Democratic National Committee and the Republican National Committee, 
regarding the staging of the 1996 debates.  All members of the CPD are current or former 
Democratic or Republican officeholders or persons closely associated with those parties.  
Since it inception, CPD membership has been divided equally and exclusively between 
representatives of the two major parties. 

27.  Prior to the CPD announcement of its decision regarding exclusion of Perot, a 
representative of Perot '96, Russell Verney, requested of the CPD that persons other than 
those with direct and substantial ties to the Democratic and Republican parties be 
included in the deliberation and decision-making processes of the CPD. See letter of R. 
Verney, dated September 9, 1996, attached hereto as Exhibit D.  The CPD refused this 
request.  Mr. Verney also requested the opportunity to address the CPD, which request 
was denied. 

28.  On September 17, 1996, the CPD issued a press release excluding all third party 
candidates, including Perot, from the debates.  See Press Release dated September 17, 
1996, attached hereto as Exhibit E. The CPD also released a letter from its Advisory 
Committee setting forth the rationale for the decision.  See letter of R. Neustadt to CPD 
dated September 17, 1996, attached hereto as Exhibit F. 

29.  The CPD communicated its decision to representatives of the Clinton and Dole 
campaigns before it was communicated to the public, to Perot '96, or to Perot. 

30.  Perot and Choate have been wrongfully denied the opportunity to participate in the 
CPD sponsored presidential debates in 1996. 


CLAIMS FOR RELIEF
COUNT I
Statutory Action Against FEC

31.  Plaintiffs repeat and incorporate by reference herein the allegations of paragraphs 1 
through 30. 


The CPD's Violation of Debates Regulations 

32.  In October 1992, in response to concerns raised about the staging of presidential 
debates in 1988 and 1992, the FEC heard testimony and received proposals for amending 
the Debates Regulation.  Subsequently, the FEC promulgated amendments to the 
regulations, which became effective on March 13, 1996, 60 Federal Register 64260 
(December 14, 1995), adding the "pre-established objective criteria" requirement and the 
prohibition against using "nomination by a particular political party as the sole objective 
criterion," as set forth in full at paragraph 18 hereinabove. Hence, this is the first election 
cycle in which these amendments are in effect. 

33.  The CPD has violated the prohibition in 11 C.F.R. Sec. 110.13(c) against selecting 
debate participants solely based upon party affiliation.  The CPD Candidate Selection 
Criteria For 1996 provide that the CPD automatically will extend "an invitation to the 
respective nominees of the major parties."  The CPD did, in fact, extend invitations to 
President Clinton and Senator Dole to participate in its debates solely on the basis of their 
being the respective nominees of the two political parties that founded the CPD. No other 
criteria were applied to either major party candidacy. 

34.  The CPD has also violated the provision in 11 C.F.R. Sec. 110.13(c) requiring that 
the criteria used to select candidates to participate in debates must be "objective." The 
selection criteria include both objective and subjective elements.  Perot met all of the 
elements that are objective.  However, the Republican and Democratic representatives on 
the CPD excluded Perot by claiming that he did not, in their view, satisfy the elements 
that are subjective. 

35.  The selection criteria at issue are unquestionably subjective.  For example, under the 
heading "Evidence of National Organization" the CPD plainly states:  "This criterion also 
encompasses more subjective indicators of a national campaign..." Similarly, the category 
"Signs of National Newsworthiness" calls for an analysis of the opinions of media 
managers, editors, columnists, journalists and pundits.  In essence, the CPD seeks to 
delegate part of its decision-making authority over the debates to the news media, whose 
professional role is to cover the news, not to shape it.  Under the heading, "Indicators of 
National Public Enthusiasm or Concern," the CPD proposes to rely upon findings of 
"significant" public opinion polls and reported attendance at meetings and rallies across 
the country.  The data considered and the interpretation of its significance invite 
subjective judgments. "Significant public opinion poll" is not defined.  The methodology 
of the polls is not prescribed, nor the questions to be asked, nor what results are 
considered determinative or indicative of a "greater than theoretical change of election."  
The criteria apparently are sufficiently flexible to permit CPD Directors to unanimously 
conclude that polls showing an overwhelming preference among voters that three 
candidates, including Perot, be included in the debates is insufficient to establish who the 
"principal rivals for the Presidency" are in the eyes of the public.  Polls can interpreted 
many ways and the question posed so as to minimize the impact of independent 
candidates and third parties. 

36.  The CPD's refusal to invite Perot and Choate to participate in the debates is in 
violation of its own criteria for determining who is to be invited.  Taking the three-
pronged subjective criteria, CPD's stated objectives, and removing its bipartisan bias, the 
criteria to determine who the "principal rivals for the Presidency" are and who possess a 
greater than "merely theoretical chance" meriting inclusion should be put this way: (1) 
Who is influencing debate?; (2) Who do the voters believe are the principal candidates?; 
(3) Who does the public believe should be in the debates? These evaluations too would 
involve subjective judgments, but they would make excluding Perot more difficult. 

37.  Through partisan application of impermissible subjective criteria, the CPD has 
illegally excluded the candidates of the Reform Party.  It also selected the major party 
candidates based solely upon their party affiliation. The CPD has violated the Debates 
Regulations mandate that only "pre-established objective criteria" are to be used in 
determining debate eligibility. 

38.  In addition to violating the provisions of 11 C.F.R. Sec. 110.13(c), prohibiting the 
selection of debate participation selection based solely upon party affiliation and 
eligibility not based on "pre-established objective criteria", the CPD has violated 11 
C.F.R. Sec. 110.13(a). That subsection provides that a staging organization may not 
"endorse, support or oppose political candidates or political parties."  The CPD's biased 
support for the two major parties is memorialized and operationalized in the historic and 
current composition of the CPD, and in the CPD's double standard for selection of debate 
participants. The Democratic and Republican candidates are invited automatically.  All 
third party and independent candidates, however, are subject to a separate set of rules - 
the significance of their candidacies is scrutinized using a predominantly subjective 
selection criteria.  This institutionalized double standard makes the CPD an organization 
which "supports" two political parties, and which "opposes" all others. 


Illegal Contributions and Expenditures by CPD 

39.  Because of the CPD's violations of Sec. 110.13(a) and (c), it does not qualify for the 
exemption from the prohibition on corporate contributions to federal candidates contained 
in 2 U.S.C. Sec. 441b by virtue of the Debates Regulation.  Section 441b of Title 2, 
U.S.C., prohibits any corporation from making "a contribution or expenditure in 
connection with any election at which presidential and vice presidential electors... are to 
be voted for..."  The CPD is a corporation; as well, it receives substantial contributions 
from corporations which it uses to pay the costs of its presidential debates program.  
Accordingly, the contributions the CPD has received from corporations for its debates 
program are illegal; the expenditures it has made for its debates program are likewise 
illegal.  It has failed to observe any of the legal requirements governing corporations 
engaging in political action. 

40.  The CPD has also violated 2 U.S.C. Secs. 433(a) and 434(a), which require political 
committees to register with the FEC and to file periodic reports. 

41.  FECA defines a "political committee" as "any committee, club association, or other 
group of persons which received contributions aggregating in excess of $1,000 during a 
calendar year or which makes expenditures aggregating in excess of $1,000 during a 
calendar year." 2 U.S.C. Sec 431(4)(A). 

42.  The CPD receives contributions in excess of $1,000 per election cycle, and makes 
expenditures in excess of $1,000 per election cycle, to serve the interest and purposes of 
the major party candidates and the major parties. 

43.  A "contribution" is defined as "any gift, subscription, loan, advance, or deposit of 
money or anything of value made by any person for the purpose of influencing any 
election for Federal office."  2 U.S.C. Sec. 431(8)(A)(i). 

44.  An "expenditure" is defined as "any purchase, payment, distribution, loan, advance, 
deposit, or gift of money or anything of value, made by any person for the purpose of 
influencing any election for Federal office."  2 U.S.C. Sec. 431 (9)(A)(i). 

45.  Once an organization is deemed a "political committee," it must submit to a number 
of FEC regulations, including the registration and reporting requirements derived from 2 
U.S.C. Secs. 433(a) and 434(a). 

46.  The granting to the CPD of an exemption from taxation under Internal Revenue Code 
Sec. 501(c)(3) (improperly so, Plaintiffs would contend) does not pre-empt the 
independent responsibility of the FEC, operating under a different statutory scheme than 
the IRS, to determine that the CPD is a corporation or political committee making illegal 
campaign contributions and expenditures, and that it has failed to register and file reports 
with the agency as required by law. 

47.  The CPD purports to be a nonpartisan voter education organization.  This self- 
characterization is demonstrably false.  The foregoing recitation of facts demonstrates 
that the CPD is a functional subsidiary of two permanent political committees, the 
Republican National Committee and the Democratic National Committee.  Moreover, in 
each election cycle it coordinates its debate program activities with two other political 
committees, - the respective committees of the presidential nominees of the Democratic 
and Republican Parties. 

48.  The CPD allows the major party candidates to dictate all of the details of the staging 
of debates.  The CPD allows the major party candidates to determine whether or not any 
third party candidates are included in the debates, and, if so, who they will be.  In 1992, 
the CPD deferred to an agreement between the major party candidates to include Perot in 
all three debates.  In 1996, there is no agreement between the major party candidates to 
include Perot in the debates, and the CPD, therefore, has excluded him. 

49.  The decision-making of the CPD is not independent, but is heavily influenced, if not 
totally dictated by the political interests and calculations of major party candidates and 
major party national committees - something it does not even bother to deny. The CPD 
receives contributions and makes expenditures for the "purpose of influencing any 
election for Federal office," namely, the election of the President of the United States.  It 
influences the election of the President by vesting control over the staging of debates and 
the decision whether to include third party candidates in the hands of the major parties 
and the major party candidates, to the extent they can reach agreement on those points.  It 
was created for this sole purpose and it has functioned to this day with this as its sole 
purpose. 


FEC Enforcement of CPD's Violations

50.  Any person who believes there has been a violation of any statute or regulation over 
which the FEC has jurisdiction may file a complaint with the agency. 2 U.S.C. Sec. 
437g(a)(1); 11 C.F.R. Sec. 111.4(a).  The Enforcement Division of the FEC Office of 
General Counsel dockets the private complaint as a Matter Under Review ("MUR") and 
is required to take steps to determine the merits. 

51.  Any complainant dissatisfied with the action the FEC takes in response to the 
complaint is entitled to petition this Court for judicial review of the agency's action or 
inaction. 2 U.S.C. Sec. 437g(a)(8)(A).  In such a proceeding, this Court is empowered to: 


"declare that the dismissal of the complaint or the failure to act is contrary to law, and 
may direct the Commission to conform with such declaration within 30 days, failing 
which the complainant may bring, in the name of such complainant, a civil action to 
remedy the violation involved in the original complaint." 


2 U.S.C. Sec. 437g(a)(8)(C). Pursuant to this provision, the Court has equitable power "to 
remedy the violation" for the FEC's "failure to act."  The statute does not limit the Court 
to the scope of administrative remedies and sanctions that the agency would be able to 
impose acting independently of a court order. 

52.  Section 437g provides that in the usual case, the civil action by an aggrieved 
complainant will not be filed until after either (a) the FEC has dismissed the complaint, or 
(b) 120 days have passed since the filing of the complaint and the FEC has made no 
determination.  However, this Court may, in the exercise of its equitable powers and for 
the purpose of fulfilling the purpose and intent of the statute, waive the exhaustion of 
remedies requirement and shorten the timeline in order to prevent the statutory right of 
action from becoming a futile exercise because of delay. 

53.  Perot '96 duly filed a verified complaint with the FEC on September 20, 1996 
("FECA Complaint"), a copy of which is attached hereto as Exhibit G.  The FEC has 
made no determination with respect to the complaint and under its practices and 
procedures it would not in the ordinary course of business make a determination until 
after the substantial impending harm described in the FECA Complaint will be realized 
and irreparable harm suffered by Plaintiffs. 

54.  The FECA Complaint accurately sets forth that the CPD has knowingly and willfully 
violated (and continues to violate) the Federal Election Campaign Act of 1971 ("FECA") 
and the regulations promulgated by the FEC to implement FECA, including, but not 
limited to, 2 U.S.C. Secs. 441b, 433, and 11 C.F.R. Secs. 110.13(a) and (c). 

55.  An order directing the FEC to impose monetary sanctions on the CPD is plainly an 
inadequate remedy for their reparable harm that the CPD's violations of FECA have 
caused Plaintiffs. 

WHEREFORE, Plaintiffs pray this Court enter an order directing the FEC to order the 
CPD either to extend an invitation to Perot and his running mate to participate in its 
debates, or else to cancel any debates staged by the CPD. 


COUNT II
Private Right of Action Against CPD

56.  Plaintiffs repeat and incorporate by reference herein the allegations of paragraphs 1 
through 55. 

57.  In FECA, Congress created a private right of action to bring a civil action in this 
Court to obtain an order or judgment directly against a violator of FECA. 

58.  The filing of an administrative complaint with the FEC against the violator is a 
prerequisite for exercising the private right of action.  Pursuant to 2 U.S.C. Sec. 
437g(a)(8), in the usual case there is a five step process: 


a. The party files the administrative complaint; 

b. The FEC either dismisses the complaint or makes no determination on the complaint 
within 120 days; 

c. The complainant petitions the United States District Court for the District of Columbia 
for judicial review of the FEC dismissal or inaction; 

d. The court declares that the dismissal of the complaint or the failure to act is contrary to 
law, and directs the FEC to comply with the declaration within 30 days; and 

e. The FEC fails to comply with the declaration within 30 days. 


59.  At the end of this process "the complainant may bring, in the name of such 
complainant, a civil action to remedy the violation involved in the original complaint." 2 
U.S.C. Sec. 437g(a)(8)(C). 

60.  Under basic principles of statutory construction and the inherent powers of the 
federal courts to ensure the effectiveness of their judgments and exercise of equitable 
powers, the statutory exhaustion requirements set forth above are not unwaivable 
limitations on judicial review. Rather, they set conditions that may be excused when 
insistence on exhaustion would threaten grave harm to the party seeking review and 
would not sensibly serve the purposes Congress envisioned in establishing that condition. 

61.  Plaintiffs have duly filed an administrative complaint with the FEC.  If Plaintiffs are 
denied the opportunity to invoke their private right of action at the present time, then the 
Court will be unable to grant them timely relief before the holding of the presidential 
debates, and any subsequent relief the Court might grant would be wholly inadequate. 

62.  In the instant case, administrative and preliminary judicial procedures set forth in the 
statute are inadequate and to exhaust them would be futile.  Those procedures should be 
waived by this Court, and this Count II should be deemed a private action against the 
CPD pursuant to 2 U.S.C. Sec. 437g(a)(8)(C). 

63.  The illegal conduct of the CPD, as set forth in Count I, threatens Plaintiffs with 
immediate and irreparable injury for which there is no adequate remedy at law.  The 
public interest will be served by the entry of injunctive relief, directing the CPD to invite 
Perot and his running mate to participate in the debates, on grounds that they have 
satisfied the objective criteria established by the CPD, or, in the event the Court deems 
application by the CPD of subjective criteria to have been permissible, on grounds that 
Plaintiffs have satisfied the CPD's objective and subjective criteria. 

WHEREFORE, Plaintiffs pray this Court enter an order directing the CPD either to 
extend an invitation to Perot and his running mate to participate in its debates, or else to 
cancel any debates staged by the CPD. 


COUNT III
Constitutional Right of Action Against FEC 

64.  Plaintiffs repeat and incorporate by reference herein the allegations of paragraphs 1 
through 63. 

65.  There exists in this nation a constitutional right of citizens to create and develop new 
political parties. Norman v. Reed, 504 U.S. 279 (1992).  Indeed, competing ideas and 
governmental policies are the core of the electoral process and the First Amendment 
freedoms of speech and association.  The right of individuals to associate for the 
advancement of their political beliefs and to create new political parties are fundamental 
rights guaranteed by the First and Fourteenth Amendments of the Constitution. 

66.  The First Amendment also guarantees that the government shall be neutral and 
nonpartisan in political affairs.  As stated by the former Chief Judge Abner Mikva of the 
District of Columbia Court of Appeals:  "The government of any democracy, let alone 
one shaped by the values of our Constitution's First Amendment, must avoid tilting the 
electoral playing field, lest the democracy itself become tarnished."  The federal 
government's duty of neutrality in electoral affairs also flows from the due process clause 
of the Fifth Amendment. 

67.  FECA and its implementing regulations require (with exceptions not applicable here) 
that corporations which sponsor federal candidate debates must be nonpartisan and they 
must stage debates in accordance with nonpartisan principles.  Most notable among these 
nonpartisan principles required of corporate debate sponsors is the use of pre-existing 
objective criteria to select candidate debate participants.  This year, CPD has utilized 
subjective selection criterion and has not been reigned in, as required, by FEC. 

68.  From the formation of the CPD in 1987 through the present, overwhelming evidence 
has accumulated as to the partisan, political character of the CPD.  The subjective 
selection criteria which CPD has adopted in three successive election cycles demonstrates 
that such criteria are designed principally to keep third-party candidates out of 
presidential debates.  Meanwhile, CPD's criteria include enough subjective loopholes so 
that when the extraordinary situation arises that the major parties desire to have a third 
party candidate in the debates, that goal can be accomplished as well. The automatic 
inclusion of the candidates of the Democratic and Republican Parties, and the use of a 
subjective "realistic chance" of winning standard solely to measure candidates from other 
parties, has resulted in this case in a de facto exclusion of Perot from the debates. 

69.  The FEC's failure to enforce the nonpartisanship requirements of the Debates 
Regulations against the CPD, and its failure to deem the CPD to be a "political 
committee," is a lapse in enforcement by the FEC that violates the a federal agency's 
constitutional duty to remain neutral in election contests.  Moreover, FEC's partisan 
enforcement/nonenforcement actions to support the interest of the Democratic and 
Republican Parties, to the disadvantage of candidates from other parties, is a violation of 
Plaintiffs' rights under the First and Fifth Amendments of the Constitution.  The FEC's 
nonenforcement in these circumstances constitutes an impermissible "tilting of the 
electoral playing field." 

70.  The continuing operation of CPD as a debates sponsoring organization using its 
current selection criteria to exclude the significant Reform Party candidacy of Perot from 
the debates is a structural inequality in the election process that would cease to exist but 
for the failure of the FEC to enforce its Debates Regulations and other FEC mandates.  
The failure and refusal of the FEC to take any steps toward stopping the CPD from 
illegally using corporate funds to sponsor debates on behalf of the major parties or 
forcing the CPD to conduct its debates in accordance with FEC regulations, constitutes an 
unconstitutional exercise of discretion, resulting in violation of Plaintiffs' fundamental 
constitutional rights under the First and Fifth Amendments. 

WHEREFORE, Plaintiffs pray this Court enter an order directing the FEC to order the 
CPD either to extend an invitation to Perot and his running mate to participate in the 
debates, or to cancel any debates staged and sponsored by the CPD, and for such other 
and further relief as this Court deems just and proper. 


COUNT IV
FEC Ultra Vires Regulations and Corresponding CPD Violation of FECA 

71.  Plaintiffs repeat and incorporate by reference herein the allegations of paragraph 1 
through 70. 

72.  The FEC has promulgated a regulation that is wholly outside of the statutory 
authority conferred on it by FECA. FECA categorically bans any contributions or 
expenditures by corporations in connection with any election to any political office, and 
makes specific definitional exemptions only in several unrelated areas.  2 U.S.C. Sec. 
441b.  However, in violation of this clear statutory language and intent, the FEC has 
promulgated the Debates Regulations that purport to allow corporations to make 
contributions and expenditures in connection with candidate debates.  These regulations 
are wholly ultra vires and constitute, by definition, invalid administrative lawmaking and 
a violation of the separation of powers.  The FEC itself took the position in 1975 that it 
was illegal under FECA for corporations to spend money on (or raise corporate money 
for) bipartisan debates which excluded other candidates. 

73.  Because these regulations are unconstitutional, any and all expenditures, made by the 
CPD are illegal under FECA.  Likewise, all contributions to the CPD from corporations 
for the purposes of intervening in the presidential debates are illegal. 

WHEREFORE, Plaintiffs pray this Court enter an order prohibiting any further 
expenditures by, or corporate contributions to, the CPD for the purposes of intervening in 
the 1996 presidential campaign, including sponsoring campaign debates. 


COUNT V
CPD Violation of Equal Protection in the Electoral Process 

74.  Plaintiffs repeat and incorporate by reference herein the allegations of paragraph 1 
through 73. 

75.  Because the CPD's entire capacity to sponsor presidential debates campaigns is based 
on an ultra vires FEC regulation, the CPD has unlawfully been delegated the FEC's 
administrative authority over campaigns and has become a de facto state factor for 
constitutional purposes. By assuming the critical public function of sponsoring the only 
televised nationwide presidential debates in the 1996 presidential campaign, the CPD is 
engaging in state action. 

76.  The CPD has violated the Equal Protection guarantee of neutrality in the electoral 
process by applying a double standard that automatically qualifies the Democratic and 
Republican presidential nominees for debate inclusion but subjecting other party 
nominees to a lengthy series of tests, some of them objective, but most of them subjective 
and arbitrary.  This bifurcated mode of selection constitutes a per se violation of Equal 
Protection, destroying neutrality in the political process, applying the laws unequally, and 
enforcing unconstitutional bias against third parties and independent candidates generally, 
and against Perot specifically. 

77.  The CPD has violated the Equal Protection guarantee of neutrality in the electoral 
process by subjecting candidates nominated by parties other than the Democrats and 
Republicans to an arbitrary, irrational, subjective and thoroughly political process of 
selection for the candidate debates.  This process has enforced unconstitutional bias 
against third parties and independent candidates generally, and against Perot specifically. 

WHEREFORE, Plaintiffs pray this Court enter an order directing the CPD to either 
extend an invitation to Perot and his running mate to participate in the debates, or to 
cancel any debates stages and sponsored by the CPD, and for such other and further relief 
as this Court deems just and proper. 


COUNT VI
CPD Violation  of First Amendment
Freedoms of Speech and Association

78.  Plaintiffs repeat and incorporate by reference herein the allegations of paragraphs 1 
through 77. 

79.  As a de facto state actor, the CPD's exclusion of Plaintiffs Perot and Choate from the 
limited public forum of nationally televised presidential debates constitutes viewpoint-
based First Amendment discrimination since they would have been certified 
automatically by the CPD to participate had they been the nominees of the Democratic or 
Republican Parties, regardless of their standing in the polls, opinions of journalists, 
reviews by pundits, and so on.  Thus, the CPD is unconstitutionally excluding Plaintiffs 
Perot and Choate from a limited public forum on the basis of their choice to associate 
with the Reform Party rather than the Democratic or Republican Parties. 

80.  The CPD's exclusion of Perot and Choate from the presidential debates violates First 
Amendment freedoms and association because it discriminates based on political party 
membership and thus constitutes an unlawful viewpoint-based discrimination. 

81.  The CPD's exclusion of Perot and Choate from the debates impinges on the right of 
the Plaintiffs to participate in the electoral process, violates their right to speak and 
associate freely, and imposes an impermissible prior restraint on Plaintiffs.  Yet, the 
decision advances no rational public interest, much less a compelling one. 

82.  the CPD's criteria for including and excluding nonmajor party presidential candidates 
are unconstitutionally vague, allowing for the kind of arbitrary and discriminatory 
enforcement and interpretation that occurred here. 

WHEREFORE, Plaintiffs pray this Court enter an order directing the CPD to either 
extend an invitation to Perot and his running mate to participate in the debates, or to 
cancel any debates stages and sponsored by the CPD, and for such other and further relief 
as this Court deems just and proper. 


COUNT VII
CPD and FEC Violation of Procedural Due Process 

83.  Plaintiffs repeat and incorporate by reference herein the allegations of paragraphs 1 
through 82. 

84.  The CPD an FEC have violated Plaintiffs' procedural due process rights by depriving 
them of their constitutionally protected liberty interests in political speech and association 
without providing them adequate notice, a fair hearing, a meaningful opportunity to be 
heard with regard to the candidate selection process, or the right to appeal. 

WHEREFORE, Plaintiffs pray this Court enter an order directing the CPD and FEC to 
either extend an invitation to Perot and his running mate to participate in the debates, or 
to cancel any debates staged and sponsored by the CPD, and for such other and further 
relief as this Court deems just and proper. 

DATED: September 20, 1996

